The '''Cape lobster''', '''''Homarinus capensis''''', is a species of small [[lobster]] that lives off the coast of [[South Africa]], from [[Dassen Island]] to [[Haga Haga]]. Only a few dozen specimens are known, mostly regurgitated by reef-dwelling fish. It lives in rocky reefs, and is thought to lay large eggs that have a short [[crustacean larvae|larval phase]], or that hatch directly as a [[juvenile (organism)|juvenile]]. The species grows to a total length of {{convert|10|cm|abbr=on}}, and resembles a small [[Homarus gammarus|European]] or [[American lobster]]; it was previously included in the same genus, ''[[Homarus]]'', although it is not very closely related to those species, and is now considered to form a separate, monotypic genus <U+2013> '''''Homarinus'''''. Its closest relatives are the genera ''[[Thymops]]'' and ''[[Thymopides]]''.

==Distribution and ecology==
{{Location map many
| South Africa
